MEDIUM|internal/reconcile/justification.go:315|extractSection's upward block-walk excludes the list-item marker line when the file:line anchor lands on a continuation line of that item. When lines[idx] is a continuation (not itself an item start) and the line above IS an item start, the loop breaks before decrementing start, so the item's first line (marker + finding headline, e.g. "1. **Forged token accepted**") is dropped from the extracted narrative — contradicting the doc comment's claim that a per-finding list item is captured. A reviewer who writes the file:line reference in the item body (common) loses the sentence that names the finding.|In extractSection (justification.go:315-322), when prev is an item start, absorb it as the block start instead of breaking before it, while keeping blank/heading prev as exclusive boundaries. Add a test: a two-line numbered item whose anchor is on line 2 must include line 1 in Justification.|maintainability|30|internal/reconcile/justification.go:315-322|claude
LOW|internal/reconcile/justification.go:201|In anchorTier the tier-1 branch (if strings.Contains(s, file) then best = 1) is effectively dead code in production: minAnchorTier is 2, so matchNarrative treats a returned 1 identically to 0, and the best<2 guard behaves the same whether best starts at 0 or 1. Its only observable consumer is TestAnchorTier; it changes no real output yet runs a full strings.Contains scan of every line for every finding.|Drop the tier-1 assignment (or the best accumulator entirely, returning 0/2/3) and update TestAnchorTier's tier-1 expectation. Confirm existing stamping tests still pass — behavior is unchanged because tier 1 was never a match.|maintainability|15|internal/reconcile/justification.go:201-231|claude
LOW|internal/reconcile/justification.go:136|matchNarrative re-scans every narrative and every line for each finding (stampJustifications loops findings, matchNarrative loops all narratives x lines, anchorTier does a substring scan per line), giving O(findings x narrativeBytes) with no pre-index. Bounded because reviews are small in practice, but purely wasteful: nothing about the narrative set is precomputed across findings.|Pre-index once: collect per narrative only the lines containing a <file>: token (or a map keyed by file), then per finding scan just candidate lines. Verify identical match results against existing tests and add a benchmark to confirm the reduction.|performance|60|internal/reconcile/justification.go:68-153|claude
LOW|internal/reconcile/justification.go:107|collectReviewNarratives reads each review.md via os.ReadFile with no size cap, strings.Split allocates a slice of every line, and extractSection builds the entire enclosing block into a strings.Builder BEFORE truncateRunes caps it at 1000 runes. A pathologically large review.md under sources/ (an open extension point) is fully materialized in memory (plus a full []rune conversion) before truncation, so the 1000-rune cap never bounds peak memory.|Cap the read (io.LimitReader or stat-and-skip above a threshold) and/or bound extractSection's block growth so it stops accumulating once it exceeds justificationMaxRunes rather than truncating after building. Verify by stamping against a multi-MB single-paragraph review.md and asserting bounded output.|performance|30|internal/reconcile/justification.go:107-340|claude
LOW|internal/reconcile/justification.go:222|A finding with Line == 0 (a file-level finding with no specific line, which the FILE:LINE grammar produces for a non-numeric/missing line) spuriously matches any review.md reference to lines 1-3 of that file: lineDistance(0, lo, hi) <= 3 promotes such a reference to tier 2, so a file-level finding inherits the narrative of whatever early-line finding the reviewer happened to write about that file. No guard requires line > 0 before proximity matching.|In matchNarrative or anchorTier, treat line <= 0 as "no line" and skip proximity matching (require a tier-3 covering match only when line > 0). Add a test: a finding with File set and Line:0 must not match a file:2 reference.|error-handling|15|internal/reconcile/justification.go:222-245|claude
LOW|internal/reconcile/justification.go:17|reviewFileName = "review.md" is duplicated from internal/fanout's reviewFile (artifacts.go:22) to dodge an import cycle. The two are coupled only by a comment; if fanout ever renames the artifact, this const silently drifts and stampJustifications matches zero files — the feature degrades to a no-op with no compile error and no test failure (findings.json silently stops carrying justifications, indistinguishable from "no narrative matched").|Extract the shared literal to a tiny leaf package both import, or add a cross-package test asserting reconcile's reviewFileName equals fanout's on-disk name so drift fails CI. Verify by renaming fanout's const in a scratch branch and confirming a test breaks.|maintainability|30|internal/reconcile/justification.go:12-17|claude
